<H3> <TI>   Armed Forces Resume Bombing of EZLN Positions </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA0501192694 Madrid EFE in Spanish 1834 GMT 5 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> PA0501192694 </F>
<F P=104>  Madrid EFE </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <FÊP=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] <LOCATION>San Cristobal</LOCATION> de las Casas, <LOCATION>Mexico</LOCATION>, 5 Jan (EFE) -- 
The Mexican Armed Forces on 5 <DATE>January</DATE> resumed bombing enemy 
positions in the mountainous zone of <LOCATION>San Cristobal</LOCATION> de las Casas, 
<ORGANIZATION>Chiapas State</ORGANIZATION>, civilian sources told <ORGANIZATION>EFE</ORGANIZATION>. 
  At least three helicopters and two planes are participating 
in the bombings that began in early this morning in a zone 
located approximately 4 kms south of <LOCATION>San Cristobal</LOCATION> de las Casas 
and where there are 13 Indian towns with a population of 5,000. 
The main towns under attack, where clashes have been held with 
scattered guerrillas of the <ORGANIZATION>Zapatista National Liberation Army</ORGANIZATION> 
(<ORGANIZATION>EZLN</ORGANIZATION>), are: Corralito, <LOCATION>San Isidro</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>El Ocotal</LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION>Corazon de Maria</ORGANIZATION>, 
<LOCATION>San Antonio Los Banos</LOCATION>, and Pinavetal. 
  The residents of <LOCATION>San Cristobal</LOCATION> de las Casas have said the 
situation has become "alarming" because the bombings started 
behind the mountain ranges and are now continuing on the 
outskirts of the city, although sources said that at first 
glance one cannot detect the presence of guerrillas. The 
sources could not say how many soldiers are involved in the 
operation but noted there are 10,000 soldiers just in the 
state's capital, <PERSON>Tuxtla Gutierrez</PERSON>, in addition to other 
contingents in <LOCATION>Altamirano</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Las Margaritas</LOCATION>, and <LOCATION>Ocosingo</LOCATION>, where 
the fighting continues. 
  Official reports indicate the bombings and clashes have 
ceased, although there is the possibility that the authorities 
have refused to give information on the new attacks to keep it 
from leaking to other rebel groups and warning them. 
  This past <DATE>Tuesday</DATE> alone, approximately 5,000 soldiers, 27 
tanks, two amphibious vehicles, 18 all-terrain vehicles, two 
fuel trucks, a repair unit, and 10 troop transport trucks 
arrived in <LOCATION>San Cristobal</LOCATION> de las Casas. Unofficial sources 
indicated that the <ORGANIZATION>Army</ORGANIZATION> had possibly uncovered several rebel 
headquarters located in the <LOCATION>Lacandona</LOCATION> jungle and those were the 
objectives being bombed at the moment. According to experts, 
the force deployed to <LOCATION>Chiapas</LOCATION> is greater than any used by 
neighboring Central American countries against a particular 
guerrilla force. This force has become a genuine military 
offensive. 
  Unofficially it is being said that, despite the <ORGANIZATION>Army</ORGANIZATION> having 
regained near total control of the municipalities of <LOCATION>Ocosingo</LOCATION>, 
the Zapatists continue to harass nearby communities. Ocosingo 
as well as the communities of Altamirano, <LOCATION>San Cristobal</LOCATION>, and La 
Margaritas have not yet returned to their daily work or school 
activities, neither has potable water, electricity, or gas been 
reestablished. 
  On the other hand, several warnings have appeared written in 
red on the walls of buildings in the municipality of <LOCATION>Tapachula</LOCATION>, 
located 12 kms from the Guatemalan border, indicating: "We are 
already here, we will continue our struggle," and describe the 
population as cowards. 
  In the meantime, rumors still persist in <LOCATION>San Cristobal</LOCATION> 
related to the alleged capture of "Commander <PERSON>Marco</PERSON>," leader of 
the armed uprising that broke out this past <DATE>Saturday</DATE>. The 
prosecutor general of the republic has scheduled a news 
conference in the next few hours to provide details on the 
numerous rumors circulating on the situation. 

</TEXT>

