<HL>
   U.S. Population Grew Less White in '80s
   As Hispanics, Asians Boosted Presence
   ----
   By Timothy Noah
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
06/12/91
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A6
</SO>
<GV>
COMMERCE DEPARTMENT (COM)
</GV>
<RE>
CALIFORNIA (CA)
GEORGIA (GA)
ILLINOIS (IL)
MINNESOTA (MN)
NORTH AMERICA (NME)
NEVADA (NV)
NEW YORK (NY)
PACIFIC RIM (PRM)
UNITED STATES (US)
WISCONSIN (WI)
</RE>
<LP>
   WASHINGTON -- The overall U.S. population became
significantly less white and Anglo-Saxon during the 1980s,
largely because of growth in the number of Hispanics and
Asians living in this country, according to the 1990 census.
   The proportion of U.S. residents identifying themselves as
white declined to 80.3% in 1990 from 83.1% in 1980. At the
same time, the proportion of Hispanics increased to 9% in
1990 from 6.4% in 1980. Roughly half of those who identified
themselves as Hispanic, the most rapidly growing minority
group, also identified themselves as white. Asians and
Pacific Islanders grew to 2.9% of the population from 1.5% 10
years ago.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   In addition, blacks became a slightly larger segment of
the <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> population, increasing to <PERCENT>12.1%</PERCENT> in <DATE>1990</DATE> from <PERCENT>11.7%</PERCENT>
in <DATE>1980</DATE>, and Native Americans grew to <PERCENT>0.8%</PERCENT> from <PERCENT>0.6%</PERCENT>.
Although still an overwhelming majority in the <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION>, whites
have shrunk as a proportion of the population from <PERCENT>90%</PERCENT> in
<DATE>1960</DATE>.
   Among Hispanics, the largest group remains people of
Mexican origin, followed by Puerto Ricans and Cubans. But the
census numbers suggest that a sizable migration of Central
and South Americans is under way. Between <DATE>1980</DATE> and <DATE>1990</DATE>, the
number of people identifying themselves as "other Hispanic,"
a group largely from <ORGANIZATION>Central</ORGANIZATION> and <LOCATION>South America</LOCATION>, increased by
two-thirds. They now represent <PERCENT>2%</PERCENT> of the population.
   People of Chinese descent remain the largest element in
the growing <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> population of Asians and <LOCATION>Pacific Islanders</LOCATION>,
followed by those of Philippine and Japanese origins. In
addition, the census found significant growth among certain
groups from <LOCATION>Asia</LOCATION> -- especially the Hmong, who are from
mountainous regions of <LOCATION>Laos</LOCATION>, and people from <LOCATION>Bangladesh</LOCATION>,
<LOCATION>Pakistan</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Sri Lanka</LOCATION>. Emigres from <LOCATION>Southeast Asia</LOCATION> and the
Asian subcontinent have been arriving in significant numbers,
but they don't yet represent a large portion of the overall
population.
   Minority groups remain unevenly distributed around the
<LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION>, with Asians and Hispanics concentrated in the West,
blacks and Cuban-Americans concentrated in the South, and
Puerto Ricans concentrated in the <LOCATION>Northeast</LOCATION>. More recent
arrivals, however, appear to be dispersed less predictably.
According to <PERSON>Jesus Garcia</PERSON>, a census statistician, growth in
the "other Hispanic" category was evenly divided among the
<ORGANIZATION>Northeast</ORGANIZATION>, the South and the <LOCATION>West</LOCATION>, though it was slower in
the <LOCATION>Midwest</LOCATION>.
   In addition, people of Mexican, Cuban or Puerto Rican
origin are more widely dispersed than in the past. The number
of people of <LOCATION>Puerto Rican</LOCATION> origin living in <LOCATION>Nevada</LOCATION> and
<LOCATION>Georgia</LOCATION>, for example, more than doubled in the <DATE>last decade</DATE>.
   "When a group gets larger, it simply cannot concentrate
the way it used to," said <PERSON>Marty Riche</PERSON>, director of policy
studies for the nonprofit <ORGANIZATION>Population Reference Bureau</ORGANIZATION>.
   Among Asians, those of Hmong descent were most numerous in
<LOCATION>California</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Minnesota</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Wisconsin</LOCATION>, while those of Pakistani
descent were found principally in <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>California</LOCATION> and
<LOCATION>Illinois</LOCATION>.
</TEXT>
