<H3> <TI>   Camacho Acknowledges EZLN Communique </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA0202034694 Mexico City NOTIMEX in Spanish 0258 GMT 2 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> PA0202034694 </F>
<F P=104>  Mexico City NOTIMEX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <FÊP=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpts] <LOCATION>San Cristobal de Las Casas</LOCATION>, 1 Feb (NOTIMEX) -- 
<PERSON>Manuel Camacho Solis</PERSON>, commissioner for peace in <LOCATION>Chiapas</LOCATION>, today 
described as "an important step" toward peace a recent 
communique issued by the armed group [<ORGANIZATION>Zapatist National 
Liberation Army</ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION>EZLN</ORGANIZATION>] operating in <LOCATION>Chiapas</LOCATION>. The <ORGANIZATION>EZLN</ORGANIZATION> 
communique states that a direct dialogue is "imminent." 
  The message is "an important step toward meeting and 
advancing the process for peace and reconciliation in <LOCATION>Chiapas 
State</LOCATION>," <PERSON>Camacho Solis</PERSON> said in a communique released to the media 
in <LOCATION>San Cristobal</LOCATION>, 1,200 km southeast of <LOCATION>Mexico City</LOCATION>. [passage 
omitted] 
  <PERSON>Camacho Solis</PERSON>, in his second communique issued on 1 
<DATE>February</DATE>, 
termed as an additional advancement the fact that the group is 
willing to broaden media coverage of the possible direct 
dialogue. 
  The armed group also agreed today to <PERSON>Camacho Solis</PERSON>' proposal 
for national and foreign journalists to cover the eventual 
negotiations, but the group excluded the private Mexican 
television networks <ORGANIZATION>Televisa</ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION>Television Azteca</ORGANIZATION>. 
  <PERSON>Camacho Solis</PERSON> responded: "My stance is not to exclude anyone 
and to make accreditation and access to the talks subject only 
to the appropriate security measures." 
  The commissioner deemed "appropriate the <ORGANIZATION>EZLN</ORGANIZATION>'s suggestion 
for the registration of the media and the procedures for 
coverage to be carried out through the group's mediator, <PERSON>Bishop 
Samuel Ruiz Garcia</PERSON>." 
  <PERSON>Camacho Solis</PERSON>, in his first communique today read this 
morning in <LOCATION>San Cristobal de Las Casas</LOCATION>, proposed to the armed 
group the creation of two "buffer zones" without an armed 
presence to ease the situation and help the civilian population. 
  <PERSON>Camacho Solis</PERSON> also announced that the <ORGANIZATION>Mexican Army</ORGANIZATION> has 
withdrawn from the towns in the conflict area. 

</TEXT>

