<H3> <TI>   Bishop Spotlights Army's Alleged Executions </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA0501034394 Paris AFP in Spanish 0235 GMT 5 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> PA0501034394 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <FÊP=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<FÊP=106> [Report by Gerardo Tena] </F>
  [Text] <LOCATION>San Cristobal</LOCATION> de las Casas, <LOCATION>Mexico</LOCATION>, 4 Jan (AFP) -- 
<PERSON>Samuel Ruiz</PERSON>, <LOCATION>San Cristobal</LOCATION> de las Casas bishop, spotlighted 
today reports on the execution of rebel Indians by the <ORGANIZATION>Mexican 
Army</ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION>Chiapas State</LOCATION>, site of fighting in the past few days. 
  There are reports that certain guerrillas captured by the 
<ORGANIZATION>Army</ORGANIZATION> have been executed, the bishop said during a news 
conference. The bishop also said that it is "foreseeable" the 
civilian population will be repressed by the <ORGANIZATION>Army</ORGANIZATION>, because there 
has not been a delimitation of the battlefields where soldiers 
are fighting the guerrilla <ORGANIZATION>Zapatista National Liberation Army</ORGANIZATION> 
(<ORGANIZATION>EZLN</ORGANIZATION>). 
  The bishop, who held a news conference minutes before the 
<ORGANIZATION>Air 
Force</ORGANIZATION> bombed a hill in the outskirts of <LOCATION>San Cristobal</LOCATION>, said that 
approximately 12,000 <ORGANIZATION>Army</ORGANIZATION> troops are deployed in the strife-torn 
region. 
  The prelate, who is involved in the defense of human rights, 
particularly that of poor Indians, said that the <ORGANIZATION>Army</ORGANIZATION>'s massive 
military response "seems to be a decision" to totally crush the 
movement, and in this framework "there are many wounded people 
who have not even been counted." 
  Ruiz called on the two sides to agree on a cease-fire so as 
to begin negotiations with the church mediation to lay the 
foundations for a concerted effort to end the conflict, which 
broke out on 1 <DATE>January</DATE> when <ORGANIZATION>EZLN</ORGANIZATION> members violently occupied five 
municipalities in the southern State of <LOCATION>Chiapas</LOCATION>. 
  He recommended that the situation be observed by national 
and 
foreign human rights observers, and he mentioned that <ORGANIZATION>Americas 
Watch</ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION>Amnesty International</ORGANIZATION>, and Lawyers of <LOCATION>Minnesota</LOCATION> are 
willing to come to the region to observe the situation. 

</TEXT>

