<H3> <TI>   Links Between Rebels, Clerics Noted </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA0201162294 Paris AFP in Spanish 1145 GMT 2 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> PA0201162294 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <FÊP=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] <PERSON>Tuxtla Gutierrez</PERSON>, <LOCATION>Mexico</LOCATION>, 2 Jan (AFP) -- An official 
communique issued <DATE>today</DATE> said the government of the <ORGANIZATION>Mexican State 
of Chiapas</ORGANIZATION> "has insisted unsuccessfully on its proposal to hold 
a dialogue" with the <ORGANIZATION>Zapata National Liberation Army</ORGANIZATION> (<ORGANIZATION>EZLN</ORGANIZATION>), 
which took by storm the mayor's offices in five municipalities. 
  The communique emphasized that the authorities have 
requested 
the <ORGANIZATION>EZLN</ORGANIZATION> members, who issued a "Declaration of War" against the 
<ORGANIZATION>Army</ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION>Mexican Government</ORGANIZATION> on <DATE>Saturday</DATE>, to "put aside their 
violent and belligerent position against the civilian population 
and the municipal authorities." 
  A day after the sudden attack by several hundred guerrillas 
on the <LOCATION>Chiapas</LOCATION> municipalities of <LOCATION>San Cristobal</LOCATION> de las Casas, 
<LOCATION>Ocosingo</LOCATION>, <PERSON>Altamirano</PERSON>, <LOCATION>Las Margaritas</LOCATION>, and <PERSON>Chanal</PERSON>, the government 
said, it is "concerned about the prevailing atmosphere in the 
municipal county seats," which remained occupied by the <ORGANIZATION>EZLN</ORGANIZATION>. 
  At first, authorities indicated that the wave of violence 
had 
been unleashed by 200 Indian peasants, but their most recent 
communique claims that the peasant groups "are infiltrated by 
people with obvious paramilitary training." The communique 
added that the infiltrators have "high-powered weapons, wear 
green pants, khaki shirts, and red and black badges, and present 
themselves as an organization of presumed liberation forces." 
  The communique pointed out that residents of the occupied 
municipalities "have said that some Catholic priests and deacons 
who uphold liberation theology have become involved with these 
groups and are supporting them with the radio communications 
system of the <LOCATION>San Cristobal Diocese</LOCATION>." 
  It noted: "The so-called <PERSON>Emiliano Zapata</PERSON> organization is 
linked to the <ORGANIZATION>Revolutionary Workers Clandestine People's Union 
Party</ORGANIZATION> and to the <ORGANIZATION>Poor People's Party</ORGANIZATION> (guerrillas), and it has 
forced the Ocisingo radio station to broadcast harangues calling 
for violence." 
  The government's communique pointed out that <PERSON>Felipe Arriaga</PERSON>, 
the bishop of <PERSON>Tuxtla Gutierrez</PERSON>, "has urged these groups to put 
aside their violent position and regretted that priests and 
deacons are accused of involvement in these incidents." 
  In <LOCATION>Mexico City</LOCATION>, <PERSON>Cuauhtemoc Cardenas</PERSON>, the presidential 
candidate of the center-leftist Party of the Democratic 
Revolution, said in a news release that "violence, whatever its 
origin, only leads to bloodshed, destruction, and greater social 
backwardness," adding that the government's duty is to inform 
people about the true situation in <LOCATION>Chiapas</LOCATION>. 
  According to <ORGANIZATION>NOTIMEX</ORGANIZATION> -- the official news agency -- 
Government Under Secretary <PERSON>Ricardo Garcia</PERSON> said the <ORGANIZATION>Mexican 
Government</ORGANIZATION> is urging peasants in <LOCATION>Chiapas</LOCATION> to be reasonable and to 
try to resolve their problems within a legal framework. 

</TEXT>

