<H3> <TI>   Army Intensifies Surveillance in Chiapas </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA1402000994 Madrid EFE in Spanish 1813 GMT 13 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> PA1402000994 </F>
<F P=104>  Madrid EFE </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <FÊP=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<FÊP=106> [Report by <PERSON>Jose Torres Hernandez</PERSON>] </F>
  [Excerpt] <LOCATION>San Cristobal</LOCATION> de las Casas (<LOCATION>Mexico</LOCATION>), 13 Feb (EFE) 
-- The Armed Forces have discreetly intensified military 
surveillance in the conflict zone in <LOCATION>Chiapas State</LOCATION> in the 
southeastern part of <LOCATION>Mexico</LOCATION>. At the same time, the <ORGANIZATION>Zapatist 
National Liberation Army</ORGANIZATION> (<ORGANIZATION>EZLN</ORGANIZATION>) is continuing its diplomatic 
offensive by forwarding letters to various social organizations. 
  The community of <PERSON>Altamirano</PERSON>, 850 km southeast of <LOCATION>Mexico City</LOCATION> 
and one of the four communities attacked by the <ORGANIZATION>EZLN</ORGANIZATION> in the wake 
of its 1 <DATE>January</DATE> offensive, remains virtually occupied by the 
<ORGANIZATION>Armed Forces</ORGANIZATION>. Cording to an official communique, however, the 
<ORGANIZATION>Armed Forces</ORGANIZATION> intend to simply maintain a garrison at the 
entrance of the community. Most people in <PERSON>Altamirano</PERSON> who do not 
have to work remain indoors most of the time and prefer to keep 
their opinions on the conflict to themselves. During a brief 
tour of the community, soldiers supported by jeeps and tanks 
could be seen on every street. Also, heightened security 
measures are in effect in the nearby mountainous area where it 
is believed the Zapatist presence is the strongest. 
  Since the conflict began, the <ORGANIZATION>Mexican Army</ORGANIZATION> has maintained 
some 17,000 soldiers at its primary base in <LOCATION>Rancho Nuevo</LOCATION>, 10 km 
southeast of <LOCATION>San Cristobal</LOCATION> de las Casas. As of 15 <DATE>January</DATE> when 
a truce was declared, the <ORGANIZATION>Army</ORGANIZATION> gradually started to withdraw 
from the towns of <LOCATION>San Cristobal</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Ocosingo</LOCATION>, and <LOCATION>Las Margaritas</LOCATION>, 
and it has set up checkpoints at the entrance of each of these 
communities. 
  Yesterday, the <ORGANIZATION>Army</ORGANIZATION> increased the number of troops at the 
fork in the road leading to <ORGANIZATION>Ranch Nuevo</ORGANIZATION> and <LOCATION>Ocosingo</LOCATION>. Ocosingo 
is an access point into the <LOCATION>Lacandona</LOCATION> jungle, which is a 
Zapatist stronghold. 
  Meanwhile, <PERSON>Manuel Camacho Solis</PERSON>, commissioner for peace and 
national reconciliation; <PERSON>Samuel Ruiz</PERSON>, bishop of <LOCATION>San Cristobal</LOCATION> de 
las Casas; and more than 300 journalists are still awaiting a 
possible meeting with the <ORGANIZATION>EZLN</ORGANIZATION>. The meeting was postponed 
several times over the past week. 
  In his <DATE>Sunday</DATE> homily today, Bishop <PERSON>Samuel Ruiz</PERSON> reiterated 
that famine is the most serious problem facing the <LOCATION>Chiapas</LOCATION> 
Indians who, according to official figures, total 1 million. 
  While waiting for the meeting between the Zapatists and the 
government to take place, <PERSON>Camacho Solis</PERSON> is maintaining contact 
with the <ORGANIZATION>EZLN</ORGANIZATION> by way of confidential letters. Meanwhile, the 
<ORGANIZATION>EZLN</ORGANIZATION> also is sending messages to other intermediators. The 
meeting between the <ORGANIZATION>EZLN</ORGANIZATION> and the government is expected to take 
place in a <LOCATION>Chiapas</LOCATION> community which has yet to be determined. 
[passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

