<LEADPARA>  The nation's minority population is becoming increasingly diverse, with a
range of new Asian and Hispanic subgroups growing rapidly and dispersing
across the continent, the Census Bureau reported Tuesday.;    While Chinese,
Filipinos and Japanese still rank as the largest Asian groups, Southeast
Asians, Indians, Koreans and smaller populations of Pakistanis and
Bangladeshis registered much faster growth over the past decade throughout the
United States.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Front  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  CENSUS SEES BOOM IN NEW GROUPS OF ASIANS,
HISPANICS  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  Mercury News Staff Writer Marilyn Lewis contributed to this story.  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     In <LOCATION>Santa Clara County</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>California</LOCATION>, the growth in the Vietnamese
population outstripped the growth rates of other Asian groups. The number of
Vietnamese jumped <PERCENT>359 percent</PERCENT> in the area, and 212 percent statewide, bringing
the total Vietnamese population in <LOCATION>California</LOCATION> to 280,223 people.;    Among
Hispanics, growth in the predominant groups of Mexicans, <LOCATION>Puerto Ricans</LOCATION> and
Cubans was outpaced by those identified as "other Hispanic," mostly Central
and South American populations including Salvadorans, Guatemalans, Colombians
and Hondurans.;    Together, the figures from the <DATE>1990</DATE> census provide a more
detailed profile of an increasingly multicultural society, with virtually
every corner of the nation drawing Asians and Hispanics from a range of
different national backgrounds.;    Most of the extraordinary growth among
Asians and Hispanics is because of immigration.;    "In addition to having all
the various European groups, we have superimposed on that Asian ethnic groups
and Latin American ethnic groups," said <PERSON>Jeffrey Passel</PERSON>, a demographer at the
Urban Institute.;    While earlier census figures reflected rapid growth among
Asians, <LOCATION>Pacific Islanders</LOCATION> and Hispanics relative to the white and black
populations, these were the first figures to break out the various rates of
increase among those ethnic subpopulations.;    The number of those
identifying themselves as Asian or <LOCATION>Pacific Islander</LOCATION> grew by <PERCENT>108 percent</PERCENT> to
nearly 7.3 million, with Chinese making up the largest subgroup at <MONEY>1.6
million</MONEY>, growing <PERCENT>104 percent</PERCENT> over the decade. But among the smaller
populations, there was much faster growth. The nation's Hmong population, for
example, increased 1,600 percent.;    Hispanics as a group grew by <PERCENT>53 percent</PERCENT>
to 22.4 million, with Mexicans growing by <PERCENT>54 percent</PERCENT> to 13.5 million. "Other
Hispanics" grew by nearly <PERCENT>67 percent</PERCENT> to about 5 million.  </TEXT>
