<F P=103> PA0601154394 </F>
<F P=104>  Hamburg DPA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <FÊP=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] <LOCATION>San Cristobal</LOCATION> de las Casas (<LOCATION>Mexico</LOCATION>), 6 Jan (DPA) -- 
The Mexican Armed Forces today attacked with mortars rebel 
positions in the mountains which surround the city of <LOCATION>San 
Cristobal</LOCATION> de las Casas, in southern <LOCATION>Chiapas State</LOCATION>. 
  The Mexican <ORGANIZATION>Army</ORGANIZATION>'s attack was launched from the region of 
<LOCATION>Maria Auxiliadora</LOCATION> hill, approximately 8 km southeast of <LOCATION>San 
Cristobal de las Casas</LOCATION>, where clashes between the Armed Forces 
and rebels of the <ORGANIZATION>Zapatista National Liberation Army</ORGANIZATION> (<ORGANIZATION>EZLN</ORGANIZATION>) have 
concentrated. 
  The new military operation in the zone, which began shortly 
after 0700 local (1300 GMT), was confirmed by residents to 
Mexican and foreign journalists who traveled to the area despite 
the defense ministry's recommendations to the media yesterday -- 
to abstain from entering the combat zone, for security reasons. 
  Six Mexican journalists were almost killed yesterday when 
machinegun fire from <ORGANIZATION>Mexican Air Force</ORGANIZATION> aircraft hit near the 
station wagon in which they traveled toward <ORGANIZATION>Maria Auxiliadora</ORGANIZATION> 
hill. 
  There is still no information if the <ORGANIZATION>Army</ORGANIZATION>'s bombardments and 
machinegun fire in the region have resulted in casualties. 
However, <LOCATION>San Cristobal</LOCATION> de las <PERSON>Casas Bishop Samuel Ruiz</PERSON> said he 
had received information about the disappearance of various 
Indians who live in the zone. 
  Clashes in the mountain zone south of <LOCATION>San Cristobal</LOCATION> de las 
Casas began on <DATE>Tuesday</DATE>, when fighter airplanes launched the 
first attack on Maria Auxiliadora hill to evict groups of rebels 
that withdrew to the mountain after leaving various towns they 
seized on <DATE>Saturday</DATE>. 

</TEXT>

