<H3> <TI>   Army Preparing Large Offensive Against Rebels </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA1001205994 Madrid EFE in Spanish 1646 GMT 10 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> PA1001205994 </F>
<F P=104>  Madrid EFE </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <FÊP=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] <LOCATION>San Cristobal</LOCATION> de las Casas (<LOCATION>Mexico</LOCATION>), 10 Jan (EFE) -- 
The Mexican Armed Forces are preparing a large offensive against 
the <ORGANIZATION>Zapatista National Liberation Army</ORGANIZATION> (<ORGANIZATION>EZLN</ORGANIZATION>) in <LOCATION>Chiapas State</LOCATION> 
and have moved approximately 15,000 soldiers, 40 tanks, planes, 
helicopters, and paratroopers to that southern area. The "final 
offensive" to be launched by the military this week will have 
the town of <LOCATION>Guadalupe Tepeyac</LOCATION> -- the only one still under rebel 
control -- as its main objective, the Mexican media asserted 
today, <DATE>Monday</DATE>. 
  Several Social Security employees have indicated that 
approximately 200 rebels are holding approximately 100 <ORGANIZATION>Guadalupe 
Tepeyac Hospital</ORGANIZATION> physicians and nurses hostage at those 
installations. The hospital is 800 meters from the Guatemalan 
border. 
  Unofficial reports also indicate that former <LOCATION>Chiapas</LOCATION> 
Governor 
General <PERSON>Absalon Castellanos</PERSON> could also be held in <LOCATION>Guadalupe 
Tepeyac</LOCATION>. Castellanos was kidnapped by the rebels a day after the 
conflict began, and the rebels announced that they intended to 
subject him to a summary trial. 
  None of the reporters assigned to the area or the residents 
of the cities negatively affected by the conflict have been able 
to confirm reports on the Armed Forces offensive because the 
roads that lead to the area have been closed by the <ORGANIZATION>Mexican Army</ORGANIZATION>. 
  There continues to be an important movement of troops at the 
colonial city of <LOCATION>San Cristobal</LOCATION> de las Casas, the entrances to 
which are guarded by tanks, and according to the media, large 
numbers of soldiers are constantly arriving. Military 
checkpoints in the <LOCATION>Chiapas</LOCATION> jungle and mountain regions have also 
been reinforced. Not even the civilians who want to take 
potable water, medicine, and food to relatives trapped in the 
conflict area are allowed to pass. Local radio stations are 
constantly broadcasting messages requesting help for the 
besieged residents or reports that they are well so relatives in 
other regions can be at ease. 
  On 1 <DATE>January</DATE> the <ORGANIZATION>EZLN</ORGANIZATION> took up arms against the <ORGANIZATION>Mexican 
Government</ORGANIZATION>, declared war on the <ORGANIZATION>Armed Forces</ORGANIZATION>, and seized several 
communities. Since then the confrontations have not stopped, 
and according to unofficial reports, at least 200 are dead and 
1,000 injured. 
  In its counteroffensive, the <ORGANIZATION>Mexican Army</ORGANIZATION> managed to push 
the 
rebels to the mountainous area surrounding <LOCATION>San Cristobal</LOCATION> de las 
Casas and is currently searching for the guerrilla's general 
headquarters, which is hidden in <LOCATION>Lacandona</LOCATION> jungle. 
  The last reported clash took place at the <ORGANIZATION>31st Military Zone</ORGANIZATION> 
garrison in <LOCATION>Rancho Nuevo</LOCATION>, 10 km from <LOCATION>Ocosingo</LOCATION>, yesterday, 
<DATE>Sunday</DATE>. The <ORGANIZATION>National Defense Secretariat</ORGANIZATION> has not reported 
casualties on either side. 
  On that same day the <ORGANIZATION>Army</ORGANIZATION> arrested Mexican priest <PERSON>Isidro 
Guillermo Badillo Brana</PERSON> at the border between <LOCATION>Chiapas</LOCATION> and 
<LOCATION>Tabasco States</LOCATION>. He is charged with commanding a group of rebels 
and was transferred to the military installations in <LOCATION>San 
Cristobal</LOCATION> de las Casas. The local church has demanded the 
parish priest's immediate dismissal and announced that if it is 
not done the church will ask for intervention by the <ORGANIZATION>National 
Human Rights Commission</ORGANIZATION> (<ORGANIZATION>CNDH</ORGANIZATION>.) 
  According to the <ORGANIZATION>National Defense Secretariat</ORGANIZATION>, the 106 
rebels 
who have been arrested revealed important information regarding 
the <ORGANIZATION>EZLN</ORGANIZATION>'s organization, its ties with Central American rebel 
groups, and the orientation of its leaders. The <ORGANIZATION>Attorney 
General's Office</ORGANIZATION> reported in a communique that according to the 
rebels' testimony, at least two of the <ORGANIZATION>EZLN</ORGANIZATION> leaders are 
Guatemalans -- Commanders <PERSON>Marcos</PERSON> and Jesus -- and it is they 
who headed the takeover of <LOCATION>San Cristobal</LOCATION> de las Casas. 
  The <ORGANIZATION>Judicial Police</ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION>Army</ORGANIZATION> have begun to search for 
both leaders, who apparently participated in the <ORGANIZATION>Rancho Nuevo</ORGANIZATION> 
clash at the beginning of the hostilities when five soldiers 
were killed. 

</TEXT>

